restitutoria, and exhibitoria, being based upon the tenor of the praetors order, and derived from Gaius (iv. 140, 142), is in Justinian a mere anachronism: interdicts aim at prevention, restitution‚ and productiori, no more, and no less, than ordinary actions. In Dig. 43. r. 1. r Ulpian adds a fourth species-interdicte which are mixed-i. e. both prohibitoria and exhibitoria.

The interdict forbidding violent ouster oi an innocent possessor is that known as uti possidetis, § 4 inl. That de mortuo inferendo is treated in detail in Dig. rr. 8; its formula ran ‘quo quave illi mortuum inferre invito te ius est, quominus illi eo eave mortuum inferre et ibi sepelire liceat vim fieri veto ;’ that oi the third probibitory interdict mentioned in the text ‘in loco sacro iacere inve eum immittere quid veto’ Dig. 43. 6; that oi the fourth ‘ne quid in flumine publico ripave eius immittas, quo statio iterve navigio deterior sit fiat’ Dig. 43, 12.

Restitutorium as applied to interdices has the same wide meaning as restituere in general ; it denotes‚ besides the restitution of possession, as in unde vi, §6 int, (r) delivery of possession where none has preceded (as in quorum bonorum, § 3inf.) 3 (a) the removal of a nuisance or demolition of an unlawsul structure, Dig. 43. 8. 2. 35 and 43.

For the meaning of exhibitorium and exhibere see on Tit. 6. 3¹ supr.
